---
// Method sheet for "On Record" (the Meridian parallax). English-only. Numbers come from the
// same view model the instrument renders, so the sheet cannot drift from the page.
import data from '@/data/meridian/parallax.json'

const { claim, verifications, sources, export_meta: exp } = data
const claimAnchors = claim.supporting + claim.contradicting
---

<div class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-4 py-14 font-mono">
  <p class="mb-2 text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-fg-faint">Method sheet</p>
  <h1 class="mb-8 font-sans text-2xl font-semibold">On Record</h1>

  <section class="mb-10 border border-line bg-panel/60 p-5">
    <h2 class="mb-2 text-[11px] uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-fg-faint">What this is</h2>
    <p class="leading-relaxed text-fg-muted">
      An instrument that reads one real research claim out of a sealed archive and shows the two
      independent verifications that disagreed about it — a <em>pass</em> and a <em>fail</em>, kept side
      by side. The point is the preservation: a runtime that refuses to resolve a genuine disagreement
      into a score, an average, or a majority. The claim stays contested; the disagreement is on record.
    </p>
  </section>

  <div class="space-y-9 text-sm leading-relaxed text-fg-muted">
    <section>
      <h2 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-fg">1. Source &amp; provenance</h2>
      <p>
        A claim-rooted export from the Meridian Research Runtime's K1-T04 archive, committed here as the
        open dataset (<code class="text-fg-muted">src/data/meridian/export/</code>): {exp.object_count} objects
        as {exp.standard}, every one content-hashed (sha256). The closure holds the two claims, {claimAnchors}
        evidence anchors for the contested one, {sources.total} source records ({sources.primary} primary
        theory preprints, {sources.secondary} secondary curated-artwork records), and all
        {verifications.length} verifications. No artifact bytes ship (<code class="text-fg-muted">artifact_count 0</code>):
        the sealed inputs are the run's material, the claim graph is its research output. Licence: the lab
        line is noncommercial (works &amp; data under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0).
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-fg">2. Cadence</h2>
      <p>
        A pinned snapshot, not a feed. The export is a versioned artifact in the repository; a rebuild reads
        exactly these bytes and no others. Git is the archive — every state of this page is reproducible from
        the commit. <code class="text-fg-muted">datePublished</code> is the maximum <code
          class="text-fg-muted">created_at</code
        > across the exported objects ({exp.date_published?.slice(0, 10)}), never a wall-clock read.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-fg">3. Processing</h2>
      <p>
        The RO-Crate / PROV metadata is a provenance <em>skeleton</em> — kinds, hashes, and
        <code class="text-fg-muted">prov:used</code> edges. The research substance (pass/fail,
        evidence-vs-counterevidence, reviewer role, confidence) lives in the object bodies. The pipeline
        (<code class="text-fg-muted">npm run meridian:refresh</code>) joins both layers into one RDF graph,
        then answers each question the page asks by SPARQL query; the verbatim findings are read from the
        bodies. Deterministic throughout: no network, no clock, no model. Both the portable graph
        (<code class="text-fg-muted">mrr-graph.ttl</code>) and the view model
        (<code class="text-fg-muted">parallax.json</code>) are committed.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-fg">Dissent, not averaged</h2>
      <p>
        The classifications and verdicts are research judgments — disclosed, attributed, and independently
        verified; the runtime's core (assembly, sealing, hashing, export) is deterministic and adds no model
        output to the authoritative record. Where two verifications disagree, invariant MRR-FR-077 keeps both
        on the record rather than collapsing them to a false consensus. Here that is a broad primary-source
        <em>pass</em> (confidence {verifications.find((v) => v.recommendation === 'pass')?.confidence.toFixed(2)},
        {claimAnchors > 0 ? ' many anchors inspected' : ''}) against a narrow, deep cross-practice
        <em>fail</em> (confidence {verifications.find((v) => v.recommendation === 'fail')?.confidence.toFixed(2)},
        one row, five findings). The claim's status — contested — is the honest sum.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-fg">4. Limits of the method</h2>
      <ul class="ml-4 list-disc space-y-1.5">
        <li>The empirical base is thin: two claims from a single run. This shows that dissent is preserved, not how often it arises.</li>
        <li>The runtime's own source is still private; only the export is open here. No “source code open” is claimed, and the open leave-behind is incomplete until the runtime opens.</li>
        <li>Independence is designed but unexercised under a single principal — the cross-practice verifier is one practice, not a federation.</li>
        <li>In this run no source backs more than one classification, so “which source carries the most” is structurally flat; it becomes informative only across an overlapping corpus.</li>
        <li>The related corpora (the encounter register, the Ulysses atlas) reference this work only by name, not by shared identifier — cross-practice questions are not yet machine-answerable.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-fg">5. Compute footprint</h2>
      <p>
        Negligible and local: the refresh runs in seconds on the committed snapshot — no cloud job, no API
        key, no network, no model. The site itself is static.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2 class="mb-2 font-semibold text-fg">6. Change log</h2>
      <ul class="ml-4 list-disc space-y-1.5">
        <li>v1 (2026-07) — first edition: the claim-rooted export, joined graph, SPARQL view model, and the parallax of the two verifications.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>

  <p class="mt-12 border-t border-line pt-6 text-sm">
    <a href="/on-record" class="underline transition-colors hover:text-fg">To the instrument →</a>
  </p>
</div>
